l at Alexandria.—Behavior of the Egyptians.—Departure for Mitylene.— We are taken by Force.—Exile to Koniah -- tCHAPTER XXXII. Route to Koniah.—Sojourn at Koniah.—Escape from Koniah — We arrive at Mersine.—The French Consul.—Arrival at Constantinople. -- tCHAPTER XXXIII . Arrival at Constantinople.— Our Position.—Designs of the Turks.— We decide to fly to Europe —Mij Nephew, Carlo Calu -- tCHAPTER XXXIV. Our Flight. — We disguise Ourselves. — We get on Board the Mail Steamer.—Our Departure.— Off at last for Europe0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMelek Hanım, an Ottoman woman of Greek, Armenian, and French heritage, accompanied her husband to various postings in Palestine and Serbia, and shared with him the frustrations of the arbitrary periodic dismissals that characterized late Ottoman politics. Her account of life in Turkey contains details of political intrigue, corruption and demonstrates the influence and mobility available to women in the official households of the Ottoman elite. Filled with maneuvers, murder, divorce, political machinations, and vengeance, Hanım's life was an attempt to gain access to property she viewed as legitimately her own. This book was written during her later exile in Paris.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aWomenzTurkey. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aSchick, İrvin Cemil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2013z978311102414108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2015z978311066303740uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146321077940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463210779423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cov